  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Poem on Numbers
  author: Cho Su
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A lifetime burdened by chronic illness—
    In the second month, sore throat strikes,
    Three nights of sleeplessness unfold.
    The four great elements? Truly illusion.
    At fifty years, still suffering thus—
    How shall I endure sixty?
    The seven emotions daily scorch and torment.
    I must rely at last on the eight paths.
    The nine realizations offer nothing to see.
    Ten decades of mere sorrowful sighs.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem employs a structural conceit, with each line beginning with the numbers one through ten in sequence, creating a numerological framework that underscores the speaker's meditation on impermanence and Buddhist philosophy. The 'eight paths' references the Noble Eightfold Path of Buddhism, suggesting spiritual refuge from worldly suffering.
